## 3. Build & install (pure‑Python `setup.py`)

```python
# -------------------------------------------------
# File: setup.py
# -------------------------------------------------
import sys
import pathlib
from setuptools import setup, Extension
import pybind11

# Helper to get the include directory for pybind11
include_dirs = [
    pybind11.get_include(),
    # If you have the real libpcapng headers somewhere, add them here:
    # "/usr/include/pcapng"
]

ext_modules = [
    Extension(
        "libpcapng",                     # name of the generated .so
        ["bindings.cpp"],                # our single source file
        include_dirs=include_dirs,
        language="c++",
        extra_compile_args=["-O3", "-std=c++17"],
    ),
]

setup(
    name="libpcapng",
    version="0.1.0",
    author="Your Name",
    description="Python bindings for libpcapng (iterator + callback)",
    ext_modules=ext_modules,
    zip_safe=False,
)
```

### How to compile

```bash
# In a fresh virtualenv (or conda env) …
python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel pybind11
python -m pip install .        # this runs setup.py and builds the extension
```

If you prefer an *editable* install while developing:

```bash
python -m pip install -e .
```

The build will generate a file like `libpcapng.cpython-311-x86_64-linux-gnu.so` (the exact name depends on your Python version/OS). Import it from any Python script as shown in the example above.

